  "prompt": "When is 70% isopropyl rubbing alcohol better than 91%?",
  "response": "70% isopropyl rubbing alcohol is often considered better than 91% in certain situations, particularly for disinfection purposes. Here are a few reasons why:\n\n1. **Optimal Concentration for Disinfection**: Studies have shown that isopropyl alcohol is most effective as a disinfectant at concentrations around 70%. This concentration allows for better penetration of the cell wall of bacteria and viruses, leading to more effective microbial kill rates.\n\n2. **Evaporation Rate**: 70% isopropyl alcohol evaporates more slowly than 91%, allowing it more contact time with surfaces and microorganisms, which can enhance its disinfecting ability.\n\n3. **Moisture Content**: The presence of water in 70% isopropyl alcohol aids in the denaturation of proteins; it helps to create a more effective germicidal effect because it promotes the breakdown of the cellular structure of pathogens.\n\n4. **Surface Disinfection**: When used on surfaces, 70% isopropyl alcohol is more effective for creating a wet film that covers surfaces adequately, allowing enough time for disinfection before it evaporates.\n\n**When to Use 91% isopropyl alcohol**: While 70% is often preferred for disinfection, 91% isopropyl alcohol can be advantageous for quick drying applications or for uses where a smaller quantity is required, such as in the preparation of certain laboratory settings or when used as a solvent.\n\nIn summary, for general disinfection, especially on surfaces, 70% is usually the better choice due to its effectiveness and slower evaporation, while 91% may be more appropriate in specific scenarios that require quick drying or higher concentrations.",
